{"title_page": "1919 Tour de France", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2019}}\n{{Use British English|date=May 2019}}\n{{Infobox cycling race report\n| name               = 1919 Tour de France\n| image              = Tour de France 1919.png\n| image_caption      = Route of the 1919 Tour de France followed counterclockwise, starting in Paris\n| image_alt          = Map of France with 15 cities marked by black dots, connected by red lines. The route formed goes from Paris, counterclockwise along France's borders, back to Paris.\n| image_size         = 300px\n| date               = 29 June \u2013 27 July\n| stages             = 15\n| distance           = 5560\n| unit               = km\n| time               = 231h 07' 15\"\n| first              = [[Firmin Lambot]]\n| first_nat          = BEL\n| first_color        = yellow\n| first_team         = Category A\n| second             = [[Jean Alavoine]]\n| second_nat         = FRA\n| second_team        = Category A\n| third              = [[Eug\u00e8ne Christophe]]\n| third_nat          = FRA\n| third_team         = Category A\n| previous           = [[1914 Tour de France|1914]]\n| next               = [[1920 Tour de France|1920]]\n}}\nThe '''1919 Tour de France''' was the 13th edition of the [[Tour de France]], taking place from 29 June to 27 July over a total distance of {{convert|5560|km|mi}}.{{sfn|Augendre|2016|p=108}} It was the first Tour de France after [[World War I]], and was won by [[Firmin Lambot]]. Following the tenth stage, the [[yellow jersey]], given to the leader of the general classification, was introduced, and first worn by [[Eug\u00e8ne Christophe]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.letour.fr/HISTO/us/TDF/1919/histoire.html|title=The Tour - Year 1919|publisher=[[Amaury Sport Organisation]]|accessdate=13 June 2011|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100717070741/http://www.letour.fr/HISTO/us/TDF/1919/histoire.html|archive-date=17 July 2010|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nThe fighting in World War I had ravaged the French road system, which made cycling difficult. As a result, the average speed (24.056&nbsp;km/h) and the number of finishing cyclists (ten) were the lowest in history.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bikeraceinfo.com/tdf/tdfstats.html|publisher=Bike Race Info|title=Tour de France Statistics|accessdate=3 June 2009}}</ref><ref name=\"chiffres\"/>\n\n==Background==\nSince the previous Tour de France in [[1914 Tour de France|1914]], it was impossible to organise the Tour de France due to World War I. Tour organiser [[Henri Desgrange]] always wanted to organise a new Tour after the war, and within days after the [[Armistice with Germany (Compi\u00e8gne)|end of the war]], the organisation of the 1919 Tour de France started.<ref name=\"reveal\">{{cite web|url=http://www.cyclingrevealed.com/timeline/Race%20Snippets/TdF/TdF1919.htm|title=THE RETURN of a Grand Affair - \"New Tour Legend: the Maillot Jaune\"|author=Barry Boys|publisher=Cycling Revealed|accessdate=3 June 2009}}</ref>\n\n==Innovations and changes==\nThree former winners of the Tour, [[Fran\u00e7ois Faber]], [[Octave Lapize]] and [[Lucien Petit-Breton]] had died fighting in the war. Two other former winners, [[Philippe Thys]] and [[Odile Defraye]] started the race.<ref name=\"veloarchive\">{{cite web|url=http://veloarchive.com/races/tour/1919.php|title=1919: Christophe in Yellow - but not in Paris|author=Tom James|date=15 August 2003|accessdate=3 June 2009}}</ref> The war had been only over for seven months, so most cyclists did not have a chance to train enough for the Tour.<ref name=\"tdf.nl\"/> For that reason, there were almost no new younger cyclists, and the older cyclists dominated the race.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://images.si.com/cycling/news/2002/07/03/timeline_5/ |title=Tour de France: Timeline |publisher=Sports Illustrated |accessdate=3 June 2009 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110805032220/http://sportsillustrated.cnn.com/cycling/news/2002/07/03/timeline_5/ |archivedate=5 August 2011 }}</ref> The organisation did not make it easy for the cyclists: with 5560&nbsp;km it was longer than all the previous Tours, and since then only the [[1926 Tour de France]] has been longer.<ref name=\"chiffres\"/>\n\nThe bicycle manufacturers had also suffered from the war and were unable to sponsor teams of cyclists. They worked together and sponsored more than half of the cyclists under the name \"La Sportive\",{{sfn|McGann|McGann|2006|pp=51\u201356}} but effectively all the cyclists rode as individuals,<ref name=\"tdf.nl\">{{cite web|url=http://www.wielercentrum.com/tourdefrance/achtergronden/tourverhalen/1919--Wanhoopspoging-levert-Firmin-Lambot-Tourzege-op-501.html |title=1919: Wanhoopspoging levert Firmin Lambot Tourzege op |publisher=Tourdefrance.nl |language=Dutch |accessdate=3 June 2009 |date=19 March 2003 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120724023018/http://www.wielercentrum.com/tourdefrance/achtergronden/tourverhalen/1919--Wanhoopspoging-levert-Firmin-Lambot-Tourzege-op-501.html |archivedate=24 July 2012 }}</ref> wearing grey jerseys.{{sfn|Cossins|Best|Sidwells|Griffith|2013|pp=58-59}} The lack of team colours made riders indistinguishable and lead to the introduction of the leader's jersey. Cyclists were divided in an A-category (professional) and a B-category (amateurs).<ref name=\"veloarchive\"/>\n\nIn previous years, cyclists had to take care of their own food during the race. In 1919, the tour organisation took care of this.<ref name=\"mdc1919\"/>\n\n==Participants==\n{{main list|List of cyclists in the 1919 Tour de France}}\n\n==Race overview==\n{{main|1919 Tour de France, Stage 1 to Stage 8|1919 Tour de France, Stage 9 to Stage 15}}\n[[File:Christophe (1).jpg|thumb|[[Eug\u00e8ne Christophe]] lead the race for most of the 1919 Tour de France, but did not win it due to a broken fork.|alt=Black and white image of man bending over his bicycle while several other men are watching.]]\nThe first stage was won by [[Belgium|Belgian]] [[Jean Rossius]]. However, he was penalised with 30 minutes for illegally helping [[Philippe Thys]] (handing him a water bottle),<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://bikeraceinfo.com/tdf/tdf1919.html|title=1919 Tour de France by BikeRaceInfo|website=bikeraceinfo.com|language=en|access-date=24 November 2018}}</ref> therefore [[Henri P\u00e9lissier]] was leading the race.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://memoire-du-cyclisme.net/eta_tdf_1903_1939/tdf1919_1.php |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120222105212/http://memoire-du-cyclisme.net/eta_tdf_1903_1939/tdf1919_1.php |archive-date=22 February 2012 |access-date=28 October 2016  |url-status=dead |publisher=M\u00e9moire du cyclisme |title=13\u00e8me Tour de France 1919 - 1\u00e8me \u00e9tape |language=French }}</ref> It had not helped Thys however, because he had to stop the race in the first stage after a large crash.<ref name=\"tdf.nl\"/>\n\nIn the beginning of the race, [[Henri P\u00e9lissier|Henri]] and [[Francis P\u00e9lissier]] were the best. They both finished before the rest in stage two, with Henri crossing the line first. In the third stage, Henri, leading the race, wanted to stop. Organizer Desgrange did all he could to change P\u00e9lissier's mind, and finally P\u00e9lissier started to race again. He was already 45 minutes behind, and the next three hours he was chasing the rest. He finally caught up, and finished second in the sprint, after his brother Francis.<ref name=\"tdf.nl\"/> After that victory, Henri P\u00e9lissier said that he was a thoroughbred and the rest of the cyclists were work horses, which made the other cyclists angry.{{sfn|McGann|McGann|2006|pp=51\u201356}} During that third stage, [[L\u00e9on Scieur]] punctured four times, and lost two hours.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.veloarchive.com/races/tour/1921.php |title=1921: Scieur continues the Belgian domination |publisher=Veloarchive |author=Tom James |date=15 August 2003 |accessdate=10 June 2009 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/5hQnQZW2r?url=http://www.veloarchive.com/races/tour/1921.php |archivedate=10 June 2009 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nIn the fourth stage, the rest of the cyclists (only 25 were still in race) took revenge on the P\u00e9lissier brothers. When they had to change bicycles, everybody else sped away from them.<ref name=\"tdf.nl\"/> Henri P\u00e9lissier chased the rest, but was then ordered by Desgrange to stop working together with other cyclists in his pursuit. In the end, Henri P\u00e9lissier had lost more than 35 minutes, and his brother Francis over three hours. The P\u00e9lissier brothers were angry at the organisation and left the race.{{sfn|McGann|McGann|2006|pp=51\u201356}} [[Jean Alavoine]] won the stage, and [[Eug\u00e8ne Christophe]] became the new leader in the general classification.<ref name=\"veloarchive\"/>\n\nAlavoine would also win the fifth stage, the longest ever in history at {{convert|482|km}}.<ref name=\"veloarchive\"/>\nChristophe was still in Grenoble at the start of stage eleven, when, at 2am tour organiser [[Henri Desgrange]] gave him a yellow jersey, so that he could easily be recognized.<ref name=\"veloarchive\"/><ref name=\":0\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.cyclist.co.uk/in-depth/1409/history-of-the-tour-de-france-jerseys|title=History of the Tour de France jerseys|last=Cunningham|first=Josh|date=4 July 2016|work=Cyclist|access-date=24 November 2018}}</ref>  The colour was inspired by the colour of the organizing newspaper [[l'Auto]],<ref name=\"tdf.nl\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.memoire-du-cyclisme.net/dossiers/dos_1919_1.php |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120322021450/http://www.memoire-du-cyclisme.net/dossiers/dos_1919_1.php |archive-date=22 March 2012 |access-date=28 October 2016  |url-status=dead |publisher=M\u00e9moire du cyclisme |language=French |title=Le premier Maillot Jaune - Tour de France 1919 }}</ref> although another explanation is that other colours were not available in the post-war shortage.{{sfn|McGann|McGann|2006|pp=51\u201356}} Previoisly the leader would wear a green armband.<ref name=\":0\" /> Christophe was not happy with his yellow jersey, and other cyclists called him a canary.{{sfn|McGann|McGann|2006|pp=51\u201356}} At that point in the race, it was likely that Christophe would stay the leader until the end of the Tour de France, because he remained in that yellow jersey after the Pyrenees and the Alps. In the penultimate stage, [[Firmin Lambot]], who was in second position, more than 28 minutes behind, attacked. Christophe, still leading the race, chased him, but broke his [[bicycle fork|fork]] close to [[Valenciennes]].<ref name=\"tdf.nl\"/> The rules were such that cyclists could get no help at all, so Christophe repaired his bicycle himself. This same thing had already cost him the victory in 1913, and would happen to him for a third time in 1922.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/in_depth/2001/tour_de_france/1364731.stm|title=1919-1929: 'Convicts of the road'|date=5 June 2001|accessdate=3 June 2009|publisher=BBC Sport| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20090604124546/http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/in_depth/2001/tour_de_france/1364731.stm| archivedate= 4 June 2009 | url-status= live}}</ref> It took him over two and a half hours, and he had lost the lead to Lambot. In the last stage, Christophe had a record number of punctures, and also lost his second place to [[Jean Alavoine]].<ref name=\"veloarchive\"/>\nLambot, aged 33, was at that moment the oldest Tour de France winner in history.<ref name=\"chiffres\">{{cite web|url=http://www.letour.fr/2009/TDF/COURSE/docs/histo_01.pdf|title=Le Tour en chiffres - Le palmar\u00e8s|language=French|publisher=[[Amaury Sport Organisation|ASO]]|accessdate=3 June 2009|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100717024419/http://www.letour.fr/2009/TDF/COURSE/docs/histo_01.pdf|archive-date=17 July 2010|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nBecause the organising newspaper l'Auto felt bad for Christophe, he received the same prize money as the winner Lambot. In addition, a collection raised money, the donors for this prize were reported in 20 pages in the newspaper.{{sfn|Woodland|2007|p=89}} Altogether, Christophe received 13310 Francs, much more than the 5000 Francs that Lambot received for his victory.{{sfn|McGann|McGann|2006|pp=51\u201356}}\n{{Clear}}\n\n==Results==\n\nIn each stage, all cyclists started together. The cyclist who reached the finish first, was the winner of the stage.\nThe time that each cyclist required to finish the stage was recorded. For the [[general classification in the Tour de France|general classification]], these times were added up; the cyclist with the least accumulated time was the race leader. From the eleventh stage on, the leader in the general classification was identified by the yellow jersey.\n\n===Stage winners===\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|+ Stage characteristics and winners<ref name=\"mdc1919\">{{cite web|url=http://memoire-du-cyclisme.net/eta_tdf_1903_1939/tdf1919.php |publisher=M\u00e9moire du cyclisme |title=13\u00e8me Tour de France 1919 |language=French |accessdate=1 June 2009 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/5hLGQXFjx?url=http://memoire-du-cyclisme.net/eta_tdf_1903_1939/tdf1919.php |archivedate=7 June 2009  |url-status=dead }}</ref>{{sfn|Augendre|2016|p=17}}<ref name=\"topten\">{{cite web|url=http://www.cvccbike.com/tour/top_ten.html#1919 |title=Tour de France GC top ten |author=Arian Zwegers |publisher=CVCC |accessdate=30 May 2009 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/5hLGQujoi?url=http://www.cvccbike.com/tour/top_ten.html |archivedate=7 June 2009 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" | Stage\n! scope=\"col\" | Date\n! scope=\"col\" | Course\n! scope=\"col\" | Distance\n! scope=\"col\" colspan=\"2\" | Type{{efn|In 1919, there was no distinction in the rules between plain stages and mountain stages; the icons shown here indicate which stage included mountains.}}\n! scop