text-align:center;\" | 9 July  || [[Bayonne]] to [[Luchon]]\n| {{convert|326|km|mi|abbr=on}} || [[File:Mountainstage.svg|20px|alt=|link=]] || Stage with mountain|| {{flagathlete|[[Honore Barthelemy]]|FRA}} || {{flagathlete|[[Eug\u00e8ne Christophe]]|FRA}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | [[1919 Tour de France, Stage 1 to Stage 8#Stage 7|7]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" | 11 July  || [[Luchon]] to [[Perpignan]]\n| {{convert|323|km|mi|abbr=on}} || [[File:Mountainstage.svg|20px|alt=|link=]] || Stage with mountain|| {{flagathlete|[[Jean Alavoine]]|FRA}} || {{flagathlete|[[Eug\u00e8ne Christophe]]|FRA}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | [[1919 Tour de France, Stage 1 to Stage 8#Stage 8|8]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" | 13 July  || [[Perpignan]] to [[Marseille]]\n| {{convert|370|km|mi|abbr=on}} || [[File:Plainstage.svg|20px|alt=|link=]] || Plain stage|| {{flagathlete|[[Jean Alavoine]]|FRA}} || {{flagathlete|[[Eug\u00e8ne Christophe]]|FRA}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | [[1919 Tour de France, Stage 9 to Stage 15#Stage 9|9]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" | 15 July  || [[Marseille]] to [[Nice]]\n| {{convert|338|km|mi|abbr=on}} || [[File:Mountainstage.svg|20px|alt=|link=]] || Stage with mountain|| {{flagathlete|[[Honor\u00e9 Barth\u00e9lemy]]|FRA}} || {{flagathlete|[[Eug\u00e8ne Christophe]]|FRA}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | [[1919 Tour de France, Stage 9 to Stage 15#Stage 10|10]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" | 17 July  || [[Nice]] to [[Grenoble]]\n| {{convert|333|km|mi|abbr=on}} || [[File:Mountainstage.svg|20px|alt=|link=]] || Stage with mountain|| {{flagathlete|[[Honor\u00e9 Barth\u00e9lemy]]|FRA}} || {{flagathlete|[[Eug\u00e8ne Christophe]]|FRA}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | [[1919 Tour de France, Stage 9 to Stage 15#Stage 11|11]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" | 19 July  || [[Grenoble]] to [[Geneva]]\n| {{convert|325|km|mi|abbr=on}} || [[File:Mountainstage.svg|20px|alt=|link=]] || Stage with mountain|| {{flagathlete|[[Honor\u00e9 Barth\u00e9lemy]]|FRA}} || {{flagathlete|[[Eug\u00e8ne Christophe]]|FRA}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | [[1919 Tour de France, Stage 9 to Stage 15#Stage 12|12]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" | 21 July  || [[Geneva]] to [[Strasbourg]]\n| {{convert|371|km|mi|abbr=on}} || [[File:Mountainstage.svg|20px|alt=|link=]] || Stage with mountain|| {{flagathlete|[[Luigi Lucotti]]|ITA|1861}} || {{flagathlete|[[Eug\u00e8ne Christophe]]|FRA}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | [[1919 Tour de France, Stage 9 to Stage 15#Stage 13|13]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" | 23 July  || [[Strasbourg]] to [[Metz]]\n| {{convert|315|km|mi|abbr=on}} || [[File:Plainstage.svg|20px|alt=|link=]] || Plain stage|| {{flagathlete|[[Luigi Lucotti]]|ITA|1861}} || {{flagathlete|[[Eug\u00e8ne Christophe]]|FRA}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | [[1919 Tour de France, Stage 9 to Stage 15#Stage 14|14]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" | 25 July  || [[Metz]] to [[Dunkerque]]\n| {{convert|468|km|mi|abbr=on}} || [[File:Plainstage.svg|20px|alt=|link=]] || Plain stage|| {{flagathlete|[[Firmin Lambot]]|BEL}} || {{flagathlete|[[Firmin Lambot]]|BEL}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | [[1919 Tour de France, Stage 9 to Stage 15#Stage 15|15]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" | 27 July|| [[Dunkerque]] to [[Paris]]\n| {{convert|340|km|mi|abbr=on}} || [[File:Plainstage.svg|20px|alt=|link=]] || Plain stage|| {{flagathlete|[[Jean Alavoine]]|FRA}} || {{flagathlete|[[Firmin Lambot]]|BEL}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" |\n| colspan=\"2\" style=\"text-align:center\"| Total\n| colspan=\"5\" style=\"text-align:center\"| {{convert|5560|km|0|abbr=on}}{{sfn|Augendre|2016|p=108}}\n|}\n\n===General classification===\n\n[[File:Firmin Lambot.jpg|thumb|upright|[[Firmin Lambot]], the winner of the 1919 Tour|alt=Man sitting on bicycle.]]\nOf the 67 cyclists that started the race, only 11 cyclists finished. On 12 August 1919, [[Paul Duboc]] (8th overall), was disqualified for borrowing a car to go and repair his pedal axle, which left only 10 cyclists in the final classification.\nIn total, 43 cyclists started as category A, and 24 cyclists as category B.<ref name=\"mdc1919\"/>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|+ Final general classification (1\u201310)<ref name=\"mdc1919\"/>\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" | Rank!! scope=\"col\" | Rider!! scope=\"col\" | Category!! scope=\"col\" | Time\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" |1\n| {{flagathlete|[[Firmin Lambot]]|BEL}} || A || style=\"text-align:right;\" | 231h 07' 15\"\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" |2\n| {{flagathlete|[[Jean Alavoine]]|FRA}} || A || style=\"text-align:right;\" | + 1h 42' 54\"\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" |3\n| {{flagathlete|[[Eug\u00e8ne Christophe]]|FRA}} || A || style=\"text-align:right;\" | + 2h 26' 31\"\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" |4\n| {{flagathlete|[[L\u00e9on Scieur]]|BEL}} || A || style=\"text-align:right;\" | + 2h 52' 15\"\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" |5\n| {{flagathlete|[[Honor\u00e9 Barth\u00e9lemy]]|FRA}} || A || style=\"text-align:right;\" | + 4h 14' 22\"\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" |6\n| {{flagathlete|[[Jacques Coomans]]|BEL}} || A || style=\"text-align:right;\" | + 15h 21' 34\"\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" |7\n| {{flagathlete|[[Luigi Lucotti]]|ITA|1861}} || A || style=\"text-align:right;\" | + 16h 01' 12\"\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" |8\n| {{flagathlete|[[Joseph Van Daele]]|BEL}} || A || style=\"text-align:right;\" | + 18h 23' 02\"\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" |9\n| {{flagathlete|[[Alfred Steux]]|BEL}} || A || style=\"text-align:right;\" | + 20h 29' 01\"\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" |10\n| {{flagathlete|[[Jules Nempon]]|FRA}} || B || style=\"text-align:right;\" | + 21h 44' 12\"\n|}\n\n==Aftermath==\nThe yellow jersey that was introduced in this tour, was so successful that it has been used ever since. Thys claimed to have worn the first yellow jersey when leading in 1913: Desgrange had requested him to wear a distinguishable coloured jersey, so his team manager found him a yellow jersey.<ref name=\":0\" />{{sfn|Cossins|Best|Sidwells|Griffith|2013|pp=58-59}} The winner of the race, Lambot, would later also win the [[1922 Tour de France]], but has become a half-forgotten figure in the Tour's history. Christophe, who lost the Tour due to bad luck, is still remembered as an eternal second.<ref name=\"veloarchive\"/>\n\nThe fight between cyclist P\u00e9lissier and tour organiser Desgrange would continue for many years. P\u00e9lissier would win the [[1923 Tour de France]].\n\n==Notes==\n{{Notelist}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==Bibliography==\n* {{cite book|first=Jacques|last=Augendre|author-link=Jacques Augendre|url=http://netstorage.lequipe.fr/ASO/cyclisme/le-tour/2016/histoire/TDF16_GH_Interactif-PROD.pdf|title=Guide historique|trans-title=Historical guide|year=2016|language=French|access-date=27 October 2016|format=PDF|work=[[Tour de France]]|location=Paris|publisher=[[Amaury Sport Organisation]]|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160817121602/http://netstorage.lequipe.fr/ASO/cyclisme/le-tour/2016/histoire/TDF16_GH_Interactif-PROD.pdf|archive-date=17 August 2016|url-status=live|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book|last1=Cossins|first1=Peter|last2=Best|first2=Isabel|last3=Sidwells|first3=Chris|last4=Griffith|first4=Clare|title=Le Tour 100: The Definitive History of the World's Greatest Race|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=-eRYAQAAQBAJ|year=2013|publisher=[[Hachette UK]]|location=London|isbn=978-1-84403-759-9|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book|last1=McGann|first1=Bill|last2=McGann|first2=Carol|title=The Story of the Tour de France: 1903\u20131964|volume=1|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=jxq20JskqMUC|publisher=Dog Ear Publishing|location=Indianapolis, IN|year=2006|isbn=978-1-59858-180-5|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book|last=Woodland|first=Les|title=The Yellow Jersey Companion to the Tour de France|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=QdMSjfvjDhUC|year=2007|origyear=1st. pub. 2003|publisher=Yellow Jersey Press|location=London|isbn=978-0-224-08016-3|ref=harv}}\n\n==Further reading==\n*{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=CWxkwQEACAAJ|title=We rode all day: The story of the 1919 Tour de France|first=Gareth|last=Cartman|publisher=Self-published|year=2019|isbn=978-1-916019-70-6}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category-inline|Tour de France 1919|1919 Tour de France}}\n\n{{Cycling stage recaps|1919 Tour de France|1|8|9|15}}\n{{Tour de France}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:1919 Tour De France}}\n[[Category:1919 Tour de France| ]]\n[[Category:1919 in French sport|Tour de France]]\n[[Category:Tour de France by year]]\n[[Category:1919 in road cycling|Tour De France, 1919]]\n[[Category:June 1919 sports events|Tour de France]]\n[[Category:July 1919 sports events|Tour de France]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2019}}\n{{Use British English|date=May 2019}}\n{{Infobox cycling race report\n| name               = 1919 Tour de France\n| image              = Tour de France 1919.png\n| image_caption      = Route of the 1919 Tour de France followed counterclockwise, starting in Paris\n| image_alt          = Map of France with 15 cities marked by black dots, connected by red lines. The route formed goes from Paris, counterclockwise along France's borders, back to Paris.\n| image_size         = 300px\n| date               = 29 June \u2013 27 July\n| stages             = 15\n| distance           = 5560\n| unit               = km\n| time               = 231h 07' 15\"\n| first              = [[Firmin Lambot]]\n| first_nat          = BEL\n| first_color        = yellow\n| first_team         = Category A\n| second             = [[Jean Alavoine]]\n| second_nat         = FRA\n| second_team        = Category A\n| third              = [[Eug\u00e8ne Christophe]]\n| third_nat          = FRA\n| third_team         = Category A\n| previous           = [[1914 Tour de France|1914]]\n| next               = [[1920 Tour de France|1920]]\n}}\nThe '''1919 Tour de France''' was the 13th edition of the [[Tour de France]], taking place from 29 June to 27 July over a total distance of {{convert|5560|km|mi}}.{{sfn|Augendre|2016|p=108}} It was the first Tour de France after [[World War I]], and was won by [[Firmin Lambot]]. Following the tenth stage, the [[yellow jersey]], given to the leader of the general classification, was introduced, and first worn by [[Eug\u00e8ne Christophe]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.letour.fr/HISTO/us/TDF/1919/histoire.html|title=The Tour - Year 1919|publisher=[[Amaury Sport Organisation]]|accessdate=13 June 2011|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100717070741/http://www.letour.fr/HISTO/us/TDF/1919/histoire.html|archive-date=17 July 2010|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nThe fighting in World War I had ravaged the French road system, which made cycling difficult. As a result, the average speed (24.056&nbsp;km/h) and the number of finishing cyclists (ten) were the lowest in history.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bikeraceinfo.com/tdf/tdfstats.html|publisher=Bike Race Info|title=Tour de France Statistics|accessdate=3 June 2009}}</ref><ref name=\"chiffres\"/>\n\n==Background==\nSince the previous Tour de France in [[1914 Tour de France|1914]], it was impossible to organise the Tour de France due to World War I. Tour organiser [[Henri Desgrange]] always wanted to organise a new Tour after the war, and within days after the [[Armistice with Germany (Compi\u00e8gne)|end of the war]], the organisation of the 1919 Tour de France started.<ref name=\"reveal\">{{cite web|url=http://www.cyclingrevealed.com/timeline/Race%20Snippets/TdF/TdF1919.htm|title=THE RETURN of a Grand Affair - \"New Tour Legend: the Maillot Jaune\"|author=Barry Boys|publisher=Cycling Revealed|accessdate=3 June 2009}}</ref>\n\n==Changes from the previous Tour==\nThree former winners of the Tour, [[Fran\u00e7ois Faber]], [[Octave Lapize]] and [[Lucien Petit-Breton]] had died fighting in the war. Two other former winners, [[Philippe Thys]] and [[Odile Defraye]] started the race.<ref name=\"veloarchive\">{{cite web|url=http://veloarchive.com/races/tour/1919.php|title=1919: Christophe in Yellow - but not in Paris|author=Tom James|date=15 August 2003|accessdate=3 June 2009}}</ref> The war had been only over for seven months, so most cyclists did not have a chance to train enough for the Tour.<ref name=\"tdf.nl\"/> For that reason, there were almost no new younger cyclists, and the older cyclists dominated the race.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://images.si.com/cycling/news/2002/07/03/timeline_5/ |title=Tour de France: Timeline |publisher=Sports Illustrated |accessdate=3 June 2009 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110805032220/http://sportsillustrated.cnn.com/cycling/news/2002/07/03/timeline_5/ |archivedate=5 August 2011 }}</ref> The organisation did not make it easy for the cyclists: with 5560&nbsp;km it was longer than all the previous Tours, and since then only the [[1926 Tour de France]] has been longer.<ref name=\"chiffres\"/>\n\nThe bicycle manufacturers had also suffered from the war and were unable to sponsor teams of cyclists. They worked together and sponsored more than half of the cyclists under the name \"La Sportive\",{{sfn|McGann|McGann|2006|pp=51\u201356}} but effectively all the cyclists rode as individuals,<ref name=\"tdf.nl\">{{cite web|url=http://www.wielercentrum.com/tourdefrance/achtergronden/tourverhalen/1919--Wanhoopspoging-levert-Firmin-Lambot-Tourzege-op-501.html |title=1919: Wanhoopspoging levert Firmin Lambot Tourzege op |publisher=Tourdefrance.nl |language=Dutch |accessdate=3 June 2009 |date=19 March 2003 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120724023018/http://www.wielercentrum.com/tourdefrance/achtergronden/tourverhalen/1919--Wanhoopspoging-levert-Firmin-Lambot-Tourzege-op-501.html |archivedate=24 July 2012 }}</ref> wearing grey jerseys.{{sfn|Cossins|Best|Sidwells|Griffith|2013|pp=58-59}} The lack of team colours made riders indistinguishable and lead to the introduction of the leader's jersey. Cyclists were divided in an A-category (professional) and a B-category (amateurs).<ref name=\"veloarchive\"/>\n\nIn previous years, cyclists had to take care of their own food during the race. In 1919, the tour organisation took care of this.<ref name=\"mdc1919\"/>\n\n==Participants==\n{{main list|List of cyclists in the 1919 Tour de France}}\n\n==Race overview==\n{{main|1919 Tour de France, Stage 1 to Stage 8|1919 Tour de France, Stage 9 to Stage 15}}\n[[File:Christophe (1).jpg|thumb|[[Eug\u00e8ne Christophe]] lead the race for most of the 1919 Tour de France, but did not win it due to a broken fork.|alt=Black and white image of man bending over his bicycle while several other men are watching.]]\nThe first stage was won by [[Belgium|Belgian]] [[Jean Rossius]]. However, he was penalised with 30 minutes for illegally helping [[Philippe Thys]] (handing him a water bottle),<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://bikeraceinfo.com/tdf/tdf1919.html|title=1919 Tour de France by BikeRaceInfo|website=bikeraceinfo.com|language=en|access-date=24 November 2018}}</ref> therefore [[Henri P\u00e9lissier]] was leading the race.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://memoire-du-cyclisme.net/eta_tdf_1903_1939/tdf1919_1.php |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120222105212/http://memoire-du-cyclisme.net/eta_tdf_1903_1939/tdf1919_1.php |archive-date=22 February 2012 |access-date=28 October 2016  |url-status=dead |publisher=M\u00e9moire du cyclisme |title=13\u00e8me Tour de France 1919 - 1\u00e8me \u00e9tape |language=French }}</ref> It had not helped Thys however, because he had to stop the race in the first stage after a large crash.<ref name=\"tdf.nl\"/>\n\nIn the beginning of the race, [[Henri P\u00e9lissier|Henri]] and [[Francis P\u00e9lissier]] were the best. They both finished before the rest in stage two, with Henri crossing the line first. In the third stage, Henri, leading the race, wanted to stop. Organizer Desgrange did all he could to change P\u00e9lissier's mind, and finally P\u00e9lissier started to race again. He was already 45 minutes behind, and the next three hours he was chasing the rest. He finally caught up, and finished second in the sprint, after his brother Francis.<ref name=\"tdf.nl\"/> After that victory, Henri P\u00e9lissier said that he was a thoroughbred and the rest of the cyclists were work horses, which made the other cyclists angry.{{sfn|McGann|McGann|2006|pp=51\u201356}} During that third stage, [[L\u00e9on Scieur]] punctured four times, and lost two hours.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.veloarchive.com/races/tour/1921.php |title=1921: Scieur continues the Belgian domination |publisher=Veloarchive |author=Tom James |date=15 August 2003 |accessdate=10 June 2009 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/5hQnQZW2r?url=http://www.veloarchive.com/races/tour/1921.php |archivedate=10 June 2009 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nIn the fourth stage, the rest of the cyclists (only 25 were still in race) took revenge on the P\u00e9lissier brothers. When they had to change bicycles, everybody else sped away from them.<ref name=\"tdf.nl\"/> Henri P\u00e9lissier chased the rest, but was then ordered by Desgrange to stop working together with other cyclists in his pursuit. In the end, Henri P\u00e9lissier had lost more than 35 minutes, and his brother Francis over three hours. The P\u00e9lissier brothers were angry at the organisation and left the race.{{sfn|McGann|McGann|2006|pp=51\u201356}} [[Jean Alavoine]] won the stage, and [[Eug\u00e8ne Christophe]] became the new leader in the general classification.<ref name=\"veloarchive\"/>\n\nAlavoine would also win the fifth stage, the longest ever in history at {{convert|482|km}}.<ref name=\"veloarchive\"/>\nChristophe was still in Grenoble at the start of stage eleven, when, at 2am tour organiser [[Henri Desgrange]] gave him a yellow jersey, so that he could easily be recognized.<ref name=\"veloarchive\"/><ref name=\":0\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.cyclist.co.uk/in-depth/1409/history-of-the-tour-de-france-jerseys|title=History of the Tour de France jerseys|last=Cunningham|first=Josh|date=4 July 2016|work=Cyclist|access-date=24 November 2018}}</ref>  The colour was inspired by the colour of the organizing newspaper [[l'Auto]],<ref name=\"tdf.nl\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.memoire-du-cyclisme.net/dossiers/dos_1919_1.php |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120322021450/http://www.memoire-du-cyclisme.net/dossiers/dos_1919_1.php |archive-date=22 March 2012 |access-date=28 October 2016  |url-status=dead |publisher=M\u00e9moire du cyclisme |language=French |title=Le premier Maillot Jaune - Tour de France 1919 }}</ref> although another explanation is that other colours were not available in the post-war shortage.{{sfn|McGann|McGann|2006|pp=51\u201356}} Previoisly the leader would wear a green armband.<ref name=\":0\" /> Christophe was not happy with his yellow jersey, and other cyclists called him a canary.{{sfn|McGann|McGann|2006|pp=51\u201356}} At that point in the race, it was likely that Christophe would stay the leader until the end of the Tour de France, because he remained in that yellow jersey after the Pyrenees and the Alps. In the penultimate stage, [[Firmin Lambot]], who was in second position, more than 28 minutes behind, attacked. Christophe, still leading the race, chased him, but broke his [[bicycle fork|fork]] close to [[Valenciennes]].<ref name=\"tdf.nl\"/> The rules were such that cyclists could get no help at all, so Christophe repaired his bicycle himself. This same thing had already cost him the victory in 1913, and would happen to him for a third time in 1922.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/in_depth/2001/tour_de_france/1364731.stm|title=1919-1929: 'Convicts of the road'|date=5 June 2001|accessdate=3 June 2009|publisher=BBC Sport| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20090604124546/http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/in_depth/2001/tour_de_france/1364731.stm| archivedate= 4 June 2009 | url-status= live}}</ref> It took him over two and a half hours, and he had lost the lead to Lambot. In the last stage, Christophe had a record number of punctures, and also lost his second place to [[Jean Alavoine]].<ref name=\"veloarchive\"/>\nLambot, aged 33, was at that moment the oldest Tour de France winner in history.<ref name=\"chiffres\">{{cite web|url=http://www.letour.fr/2009/TDF/COURSE/docs/histo_01.pdf|title=Le Tour en chiffres - Le palmar\u00e8s|language=French|publisher=[[Amaury Sport Organisation|ASO]]|accessdate=3 June 2009|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100717024419/http://www.letour.fr/2009/TDF/COURSE/docs/histo_01.pdf|archive-date=17 July 2010|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nBecause the organising newspaper l'Auto felt bad for Christophe, he received the same prize money as the winner Lambot. In addition, a collection raised money, the donors for this prize were reported in 20 pages in the newspaper.{{sfn|Woodland|2007|p=89}} Altogether, Christophe received 13310 Francs, much more than the 5000 Francs that Lambot received for his victory.{{sfn|McGann|McGann|2006|pp=51\u201356}}\n{{Clear}}\n\n==Results==\n\nIn each stage, all cyclists started together. The cyclist who reached the finish first, was the winner of the stage.\nThe time that each cyclist required to finish the stage was recorded. For the [[general classification in the Tour de France|general classification]], these times were added up; the cyclist with the least accumulated time was the race leader. From the eleventh stage on, the leader in the general classification was identified by the yellow jersey.\n\n===Stage winners===\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|+ Stage characteristics and winners<ref name=\"mdc1919\">{{cite web|url=http://memoire-du-cyclisme.net/eta_tdf_1903_1939/tdf1919.php |publisher=M\u00e9moire du cyclisme |title=13\u00e8me Tour de France 1919 |language=French |accessdate=1 June 2009 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/5hLGQXFjx?url=http://memoire-du-cyclisme.net/eta_tdf_1903_1939/tdf1919.php |archivedate=7 June 2009  |url-status=dead }}</ref>{{sfn|Augendre|2016|p=17}}<ref name=\"topten\">{{cite web|url=http://www.cvccbike.com/tour/top_ten.html#1919 |title=Tour de France GC top ten |author=Arian Zwegers |publisher=CVCC |accessdate=30 May 2009 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/5hLGQujoi?url=http://www.cvccbike.com/tour/top_ten.html |archivedate=7 June 2009 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" | Stage\n! scope=\"col\" | Date\n! scope=\"col\" | Course\n! scope=\"col\" | Distance\n! scope=\"col\" colspan=\"2\" | Type{{efn|In 1919, there was no distinction in the rules between plain stages and mountain stages; the icons shown here indicate which stage included mountains.}}\n! scope=\"col\" | Winner\n! scope=\"col\" | Race leader\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | [[1919 Tour de France, Stage 1 to Stage 8#Stage 1|1]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" | 29 June  || [[Paris]] to [[Le Havre]]\n| {{convert|388|km|mi|abbr=on}} || [[File:Plainstage.svg|20px|alt=|link=]] || Plain stage|| {{flagathlete|[[Jean Rossius]]|BEL}} || {{flagathlete|[[Henri P\u00e9lissier]]|FRA}}{{efn|The winner of stage 1, Rossius, received a 30 minute penalty, so after stage 1 Henri P\u00e9lissier, who finished second, was leading the race.}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | [[1919 Tour de France, Stage 1 to Stage 8#Stage 2|2]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" | 1 July  || [[Le Havre]] to [[Cherbourg]]\n| {{convert|364|km|mi|abbr=on}} || [[File:Plainstage.svg|20px|alt=|link=]] || Plain stage|| {{flagathlete|[[Henri P\u00e9lissier]]|FRA}} || {{flagathlete|[[Henri P\u00e9lissier]]|FRA}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | [[1919 Tour de France, Stage 1 to Stage 8#Stage 3|3]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" | 3 July  || [[Cherbourg]] to [[Brest, France|Brest]]\n| {{convert|405|km|mi|abbr=on}} || [[File:Plainstage.svg|20px|alt=|link=]] || Plain stage|| {{flagathlete|[[Francis P\u00e9lissier]]|FRA}} || {{flagathlete|[[Henri P\u00e9lissier]]|FRA}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | [[1919 Tour de France, Stage 1 to Stage 8#Stage 4|4]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" | 5 July  || [[Brest, France|Brest]] to [[Les Sables-d'Olonne]]\n| {{convert|412|km|mi|abbr=on}} || [[File:Plainstage.svg|20px|alt=|link=]] || Plain stage|| {{flagathlete|[[Jean Alavoine]]|FRA}} || {{flagathlete|[[Eug\u00e8ne Christophe]]|FRA}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | [[1919 Tour de France, Stage 1 to Stage 8#Stage 5|5]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" | 7 July  || [[Les Sables-d'Olonne]] to [[Bayonne]]\n| {{convert|482|km|mi|abbr=on}} || [[File:Plainstage.svg|20px|alt=|link=]] || Plain stage|| {{flagathlete|[[Jean Alavoine]]|FRA}}|| {{flagathlete|[[Eug\u00e8ne Christophe]]|FRA}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | [[1919 Tour de France, Stage 1 to Stage 8#Stage 6|6]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" | 9 July  || [[Bayonne]] to [[Luchon]]\n| {{convert|326|km|mi|abbr=on}} || [[File:Mountainstage.svg|20px|alt=|link=]] || Stage with mountain|| {{flagathlete|[[Honore Barthelemy]]|FRA}} || {{flagathlete|[[Eug\u00e8ne Christophe]]|FRA}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | [[1919 Tour de France, Stage 1 to Stage 8#Stage 7|7]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" | 11 July  || [[Luchon]] to [[Perpignan]]\n| {{convert|323|km|mi|abbr=on}} || [[File:Mountainstage.svg|20px|alt=|link=]] || Stage with mountain|| {{flagathlete|[[Jean Alavoine]]|FRA}} || {{flagathlete|[[Eug\u00e8ne Christophe]]|FRA}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | [[1919 Tour de France, Stage 1 to Stage 8#Stage 8|8]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" | 13 July  || [[Perpignan]] to [[Marseille]]\n| {{convert|370|km|mi|abbr=on}} || [[File:Plainstage.svg|20px|alt=|link=]] || Plain stage|| {{flagathlete|[[Jean Alavoine]]|FRA}} || {{flagathlete|[[Eug\u00e8ne Christophe]]|FRA}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | [[1919 Tour de France, Stage 9 to Stage 15#Stage 9|9]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" | 15 July  || [[Marseille]] to [[Nice]]\n| {{convert|338|km|mi|abbr=on}} || [[File:Mountainstage.svg|20px|alt=|link=]] || Stage with mountain|| {{flagathlete|[[Honor\u00e9 Barth\u00e9lemy]]|FRA}} || {{flagathlete|[[Eug\u00e8ne Christophe]]|FRA}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | [[1919 Tour de France, Stage 9 to Stage 15#Stage 10|10]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" | 17 July  || [[Nice]] to [[Grenoble]]\n| {{convert|333|km|mi|abbr=on}} || [[File:Mountainstage.svg|20px|alt=|link=]] || Stage with mountain|| {{flagathlete|[[Honor\u00e9 Barth\u00e9lemy]]|FRA}} || {{flagathlete|[[Eug\u00e8ne Christophe]]|FRA}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | [[1919 Tour de France, Stage 9 to Stage 15#Stage 11|11]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" | 19 July  || [[Grenoble]] to [[Geneva]]\n| {{convert|325|km|mi|abbr=on}} || [[File:Mountainstage.svg|20px|alt=|link=]] || Stage with mountain|| {{flagathlete|[[Honor\u00e9 Barth\u00e9lemy]]|FRA}} || {{flagathlete|[[Eug\u00e8ne Christophe]]|FRA}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | [[1919 Tour de France, Stage 9 to Stage 15#Stage 12|12]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" | 21 July  || [[Geneva]] to [[Strasbourg]]\n| {{convert|371|km|mi|abbr=on}} || [[File:Mountainstage.svg|20px|alt=|link=]] || Stage with mountain|| {{flagathlete|[[Luigi Lucotti]]|ITA|1861}} || {{flagathlete|[[Eug\u00e8ne Christophe]]|FRA}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | [[1919 Tour de France, Stage 9 to Stage 15#Stage 13|13]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" | 23 July  || [[Strasbourg]] to [[Metz]]\n| {{convert|315|km|mi|abbr=on}} || [[File:Plainstage.svg|20px|alt=|link=]] || Plain stage|| {{flagathlete|[[Luigi Lucotti]]|ITA|1861}} || {{flagathlete|[[Eug\u00e8ne Christophe]]|FRA}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | [[1919 Tour de France, Stage 9 to Stage 15#Stage 14|14]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" | 25 July  || [[Metz]] to [[Dunkerque]]\n| {{convert|468|km|mi|abbr=on}} || [[File:Plainstage.svg|20px|alt=|link=]] || Plain stage|| {{flagathlete|[[Firmin Lambot]]|BEL}} || {{flagathlete|[[Firmin Lambot]]|BEL}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | [[1919 Tour de France, Stage 9 to Stage 15#Stage 15|15]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" | 27 July|| [[Dunkerque]] to [[Paris]]\n| {{convert|340|km|mi|abbr=on}} || [[File:Plainstage.svg|20px|alt=|link=]] || Plain stage|| {{flagathlete|[[Jean Alavoine]]|FRA}} || {{flagathlete|[[Firmin Lambot]]|BEL}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" |\n| colspan=\"2\" style=\"text-align:center\"| Total\n| colspan=\"5\" style=\"text-align:center\"| {{convert|5560|km|0|abbr=on}}{{sfn|Augendre|2016|p=108}}\n|}\n\n===General classification===\n\n[[File:Firmin Lambot.jpg|thumb|upright|[[Firmin Lambot]], the winner of the 1919 Tour|alt=Man sitting on bicycle.]]\nOf the 67 cyclists that started the race, only 11 cyclists finished. On 12 August 1919, [[Paul Duboc]] (8th overall), was disqualified for borrowing a car to go and repair his pedal axle, which left only 10 cyclists in the final classification.\nIn total, 43 cyclists started as category A, and 24 cyclists as category B.<ref name=\"mdc1919\"/>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|+ Final general classification (1\u201310)<ref name=\"mdc1919\"/>\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" | Rank!! scope=\"col\" | Rider!! scope=\"col\" | Category!! scope=\"col\" | Time\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" |1\n| {{flagathlete|[[Firmin Lambot]]|BEL}} || A || style=\"text-align:right;\" | 231h 07' 15\"\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" |2\n| {{flagathlete|[[Jean Alavoine]]|FRA}} || A || style=\"text-align:right;\" | + 1h 42' 54\"\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" |3\n| {{flagathlete|[[Eug\u00e8ne Christophe]]|FRA}} || A || style=\"text-align:right;\" | + 2h 26' 31\"\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" |4\n| {{flagathlete|[[L\u00e9on Scieur]]|BEL}} || A || style=\"text-align:right;\" | + 2h 52' 15\"\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" |5\n| {{flagathlete|[[Honor\u00e9 Barth\u00e9lemy]]|FRA}} || A || style=\"text-align:right;\" | + 4h 14' 22\"\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" |6\n| {{flagathlete|[[Jacques Coomans]]|BEL}} || A || style=\"text-align:right;\" | + 15h 21' 34\"\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" |7\n| {{flagathlete|[[Luigi Lucotti]]|ITA|1861}} || A || style=\"text-align:right;\" | + 16h 01' 12\"\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" |8\n| {{flagathlete|[[Joseph Van Daele]]|BEL}} || A || style=\"text-align:right;\" | + 18h 23' 02\"\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" |9\n| {{flagathlete|[[Alfred Steux]]|BEL}} || A || style=\"text-align:right;\" | + 20h 29' 01\"\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" |10\n| {{flagathlete|[[Jules Nempon]]|FRA}} || B || style=\"text-align:right;\" | + 21h 44' 12\"\n|}\n\n==Aftermath==\nThe yellow jersey that was introduced in this tour, was so successful that it has been used ever since. Thys claimed to have worn the first yellow jersey when leading in 1913: Desgrange had requested him to wear a distinguishable coloured jersey, so his team manager found him a yellow jersey.<ref name=\":0\" />{{sfn|Cossins|Best|Sidwells|Griffith|2013|pp=58-59}} The winner of the race, Lambot, would later also win the [[1922 Tour de France]], but has become a half-forgotten figure in the Tour's history. Christophe, who lost the Tour due to bad luck, is still remembered as an eternal second.<ref name=\"veloarchive\"/>\n\nThe fight between cyclist P\u00e9lissier and tour organiser Desgrange would continue for many years. P\u00e9lissier would win the [[1923 Tour de France]].\n\n==Notes==\n{{Notelist}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==Bibliography==\n* {{cite book|first=Jacques|last=Augendre|author-link=Jacques Augendre|url=http://netstorage.lequipe.fr/ASO/cyclisme/le-tour/2016/histoire/TDF16_GH_Interactif-PROD.pdf|title=Guide historique|trans-title=Historical guide|year=2016|language=French|access-date=27 October 2016|format=PDF|work=[[Tour de France]]|location=Paris|publisher=[[Amaury Sport Organisation]]|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160817121602/http://netstorage.lequipe.fr/ASO/cyclisme/le-tour/2016/histoire/TDF16_GH_Interactif-PROD.pdf|archive-date=17 August 2016|url-status=live|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book|last1=Cossins|first1=Peter|last2=Best|first2=Isabel|last3=Sidwells|first3=Chris|last4=Griffith|first4=Clare|title=Le Tour 100: The Definitive History of the World's Greatest Race|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=-eRYAQAAQBAJ|year=2013|publisher=[[Hachette UK]]|location=London|isbn=978-1-84403-759-9|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book|last1=McGann|first1=Bill|last2=McGann|first2=Carol|title=The Story of the Tour de France: 1903\u20131964|volume=1|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=jxq20JskqMUC|publisher=Dog Ear Publishing|location=Indianapolis, IN|year=2006|isbn=978-1-59858-180-5|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book|last=Woodland|first=Les|title=The Yellow Jersey Companion to the Tour de France|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=QdMSjfvjDhUC|year=2007|origyear=1st. pub. 2003|publisher=Yellow Jersey Press|location=London|isbn=978-0-224-08016-3|ref=harv}}\n\n==Further reading==\n*{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=CWxkwQEACAAJ|title=We rode all day: The story of the 1919 Tour de France|first=Gareth|last=Cartman|publisher=Self-published|year=2019|isbn=978-1-916019-70-6}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category-inline|Tour de France 1919|1919 Tour de France}}\n\n{{Cycling stage recaps|1919 Tour de France|1|8|9|15}}\n{{Tour de France}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:1919 Tour De France}}\n[[Category:1919 Tour de France| ]]\n[[Category:1919 in French sport|Tour de France]]\n[[Category:Tour de France by year]]\n[[Category:1919 in road cycling|Tour De France, 1919]]\n[[Category:June 1919 sports events|Tour de France]]\n[[Category:July 1919 sports events|Tour de France]]\n", "name_user": "BaldBoris", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eInnovations and changes:Changes from the previous Tour \u2192 Innovations and changes", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/1919_Tour_de_France"}
{"title_page": "Ljig", "text_new": "{{Infobox settlement\n| native_name       = \u0409\u0438\u0433\n| native_name_lang  = sr\n| official_name     = Ljig\n| other_name        = \n| settlement_type   = [[List of cities in Serbia|Town]] and [[Municipalities and cities of Serbia|municipality]]\n| image_shield      = Grb Ljiga.png\n| image_flag        = FLAG_Ljig.gif\n| image_skyline     = Ljig_spomenik1.jpg\n| image_caption     = Monument to the [[Yugoslav Partisans|Partisans]]\n| image_map         = Municipalities of Serbia Ljig.png\n| map_caption       = Location of the municipality of Ljig within Serbia\n| mapsize           = \n| coordinates       = {{coord|44|13|N|20|11|E|region:RS|display=inline,title}}\n| subdivision_type        = [[List of sovereign states|Country]]\n| subdivision_name        = {{flag|Serbia}}\n| subdivision_type1       = [[Subdivisions of Serbia|Region]]\n| subdivision_name1       = [[\u0160umadija and Western Serbia]]\n| subdivision_type2       = [[List of districts of Serbia|District]]\n| subdivision_name2       = [[Kolubara District|Kolubara]]\n| parts_type        = Settlements\n| parts_style       = para\n| p1                = 27\n| leader_title      = Mayor\n| leader_name       = Dragan Lazarevi\u0107\n| area_blank1_title = Town\n| area_blank1_km2   = 5.42\n| area_blank2_title = Municipality\n| area_blank2_km2   = 279\n| area_footnotes    = <ref>{{Serbian municipalities 2006}}</ref>\n| elevation_m       = 150\n| population_footnotes = <ref>{{Serbian census 2011}}</ref>\n| population_as_of  = 2011 census\n| population_blank1_title = Town\n| population_blank1 = 5000\n| population_density_blank1_km2 = auto\n| population_blank2_title = Municipality\n| population_blank2 = 12730\n| population_density_blank2_km2 = auto\n| timezone          = [[Central European Time|CET]]\n| utc_offset        = +1\n| timezone_DST      = [[Central European Summer Time|CEST]]\n| utc_offset_DST    = +2\n| postal_code_type  = [[Postal codes in Serbia|Postal code]]\n| postal_code       = 14240\n| area_code_type    = [[Telephone numbers in Serbia|Area code]]\n| area_code         = +381(0)14\n| blank_name        = [[Vehicle registration plates of Serbia|Car plates]]\n| blank_info        = VA\n| website           = {{url|www.ljig.rs}}\n}}\n\n'''Ljig''' ({{lang-sr-cyr|\u0409\u0438\u0433}}) is a town and municipality located in the [[Kolubara District]] of western Serbia. It has a population of 3,219 inhabitants{{ref|town}}, while the municipality has a total of 12,730 inhabitants.{{ref|census}}\n\nIt is surrounded by [[Mount Rajac]] and [[Mount Rudnik]].\n\n==History==\nThe recorded history of the Ljig settlement itself begins in 1911, when a railroad was built between [[Lajkovac]] and [[Gornji Milanovac]]. The area, however, has a long history. The [[Di\u0107i]] church was founded by Serbian nobleman [[Vlgdrag]], who was buried here in 1327.<ref>{{cite book|last=Stamenkovi\u0107|first=Srboljub \u0110.|title=Geografska enciklopedija: naselja Srbije|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=AHEtAQAAIAAJ|year=2002|publisher=Geografski fakultet|page=499}}</ref> The ruins of the medieval [[Vavedenje Monastery]] include impressive [[sarcophagus|sarcophagi]] dating from the 15th century, believed to belong to the Serbian despots [[Stefan Brankovi\u0107]] and [[\u0110ura\u0111 Brankovi\u0107]]. According to legend, Djuradj's wife, Jerina, was buried there as well.\n\nAn early reference to \"Ljig\" can be found in the 17th century records of [[Evliya \u00c7elebi]], which describe \"LIGmehri\" (the [[Ljig River]]) rising from Kara Dag in the village Baht (today's [[Ba (Serbia)|Ba]]) and flowing into the Kolubara River near [[Valjevo]].  No settlement in the area was known to the [[Austrian Empire|Austrian]]s when they occupied Serbia from 1717 to 1739. By 1818, however, the nearby settlement [[Gukosi]] had grown to 50 homes.\n\nA railway station was built in 1917 near the present-day center of Ljig.  This lower area under the Guko\u0161i hill includes a small settlement with a municipal court, school, inn, two stores, two textile mills, three tailors and several houses, and when still part of Guko\u0161i had been referred to as the area \"on the [[Ljig River]].\"\n\nDuring [[World War I]], the [[Battle of Kolubara]] was fought nearby, making this area significant in history of Serbia and of war, and in military science. A monument memorializing the battle has been erected on Rajac Mountain.\n\nLjig separated from Guko\u0161i in 1922, and by 1930 a school, health center and church were built. Prior to that time, Ljig residents had worshipped in Moravci.\n\n==Settlements==\nThe town of Ljig is the economic and cultural center of the municipality with a primary school founded in 1907, a [[high school]], a public library with a [[movie theater|cinema]], a health center and a [[post office]].\n\nAside from the town of Ljig, the following settlements are part of municipality of Ljig:\n{{div col|colwidth=12em}}\n* [[Ivanovci (Ljig)|Ivanovci]]\n* [[Kozelj]]\n* [[Lalinci]]\n* [[Veli\u0161evac]]\n* [[Babaji\u0107]]\n* [[Ba (Ljig)|Ba]]\n* [[Kadina Luka]]\n* [[Kalanjevci]]\n* [[Jaj\u010di\u0107]]\n* [[Liplje, Ljig|Liplje]]\n* [[Moravci, Serbia|Moravci]]\n* [[Stavica]]\n* [[Guko\u0161]]\n* [[Milavac]]\n* [[Bran\u010di\u0107]]\n* [[Poljanice, Serbia|Poljanice]]\n* [[Latkovi\u0107]]\n* [[Slavkovica]]\n* [[Pale\u017enica]]\n* [[Belanovica]]\n* [[Bo\u0161njanovi\u0107]]\n* [[Donji Banjani]]\n* [[Di\u0107i]]\n* [[Cvetanovac]]\n* [[\u017divkovci]] \n* [[\u0160utci]]\n{{div col end}}\n\n==Demographics==\n{{Historical populations\n|type =\n| percentages = pagr\n|1948|20190 |1953|20697 |1961|19662 |1971|18549 |1981|17620 |1991|15912 |2002|14629 |2011|12754\n| source = <ref>{{cite web|title=2011 Census of Population, Households and Dwellings in the Republic of Serbia|url=http://pod2.stat.gov.rs/ObjavljenePublikacije/Popis2011/Knjiga20.pdf|website=stat.gov.rs|publisher=Statistical Office of the Republic of Serbia|accessdate=18 August 2017}}</ref>\n}}\nAccording to the 2011 census results, the municipality of Ljig has 12,754 inhabitants.\n\n===Ethnic groups===\nThe ethnic composition of the municipality:<ref>{{cite web|title=Population by ethnicity and sex, by municipalities and cities|url=http://pod2.stat.gov.rs/ObjavljenePublikacije/Popis2011/Nacionalna%20pripadnost-Ethnicity.pdf|website=stat.gov.rs|publisher=Statistical Office of Serbia|accessdate=18 August 2017}}</ref>\n{|class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Ethnic group\n! Population\n|-\n|style=\"background:#F5F5DC;\"|[[Serbs]]||align=\"right\"|12,145\n|-\n|style=\"background:#F5F5DC;\"|[[Romani people in Serbia|Roma]]||align=\"right\"|160\n|-\n|style=\"background:#F5F5DC;\"|[[Montenegrins of Serbia|Montenegrins]]||align=\"right\"|17\n|-\n|style=\"background:#F5F5DC;\"|[[Yugoslavs in Serbia|Yugoslavs]]||align=\"right\"|11\n|-\n|style=\"background:#F5F5DC;\"|[[Macedonians in Serbia|Macedonians]]||align=\"right\"|8\n|-\n|style=\"background:#F5F5DC;\"|[[Croats of Serbia|Croats]]||align=\"right\"|7\n|-\n|style=\"background:#F5F5DC;\"|Others||align=\"right\"|406\n|-\n|style=\"background:#F0F0F0;\"|'''Total'''||align=\"right\"|12,754\n|}\n\n==Economy==\nThe following table gives a preview of total number of registered people employed in legal entities per their core activity (as of 2018):<ref name=\"stats18\">{{cite web|title=MUNICIPALITIES AND REGIONS OF THE REPUBLIC OF SERBIA, 2019.|url=https://publikacije.stat.gov.rs/G2019/PdfE/G201913046.pdf|website=stat.gov.rs|publisher=[[Statistical Office of the Republic of Serbia]]|date=25 December 2019|accessdate=28 December 2019}}</ref>\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\" style=\"font-size:95%;\"\n|-\n! Activity\n! Total\n|-\n|Agriculture, forestry and fishing||align=\"right\"|22\n|-\n|Mining and quarrying||align=\"right\"|159\n|-\n|Manufacturing||align=\"right\"|393\n|-\n|Electricity, gas, steam and air conditioning supply||align=\"right\"|4\n|-\n|Water supply; sewerage, waste management and remediation activiti