est''\n</gallery>\n\n==Notes and references==\n;Notes\n# {{note|town}}[https://web.archive.org/web/20051001081834/http://www.ear.eu.int/publications/main/news-a1a2b3bi4.htm \"Plum brandy, the Internet and the world\"], European Agency for Reconstruction press release on Ljig\n# {{note|census}}[https://web.archive.org/web/20101113152636/http://webrzs.stat.gov.rs/axd/Zip/eSn31.pdf 2002 Serbian National Census]\n\n;References\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Ljig}}\n* {{official website|http://www.ljig.rs}}\n\n{{Municipalities of Serbia}}\n\n[[Category:Populated places in Kolubara District]]\n[[Category:\u0160umadija]]\n[[Category:Municipalities and cities of \u0160umadija and Western Serbia]]\n", "name_user": "Djura777", "label": "safe", "comment": "Updated mayor name: source:ljig.rs", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ljig"}
{"title_page": "1914 Tour de France", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2019}}\n{{Use British English|date=May 2019}}\n{{Infobox cycling race report\n| name               = 1914 Tour de France\n| image              = Tour de France 1914 map-fr.svg\n| image_caption      = Route of the 1914 Tour de France followed counterclockwise, starting in Paris\n| image_alt          = Map of France with the route of the 1914 Tour de France on it, showing that the race started in Paris, went clockwise through France and ended in Paris after fifteen stages.\n| image_size         = 300px\n| date               = 28 June \u2013 26 July\n| stages             = 15\n| distance           = 5380\n| unit               = km\n| time               = 200h 28' 48\"\n| first              = [[Philippe Thys]]\n| first_nat          = BEL\n| first_team         = Peugeot\u2013Wolber\n| second             = [[Henri P\u00e9lissier]]\n| second_nat         = FRA\n| second_team        = Peugeot\u2013Wolber\n| third              = [[Jean Alavoine]]\n| third_nat          = FRA\n| third_team         = Peugeot\u2013Wolber\n| previous           = [[1913 Tour de France|1913]]\n| next               = [[1919 Tour de France|1919]]\n}}\nThe '''1914 Tour de France''' was the 12th edition of the [[Tour de France]], taking place in 15 stages from 28 June to 26 July. The total distance was {{convert|5380|km|mi}} and the average speed of the riders was {{convert|26.835|km/h|mph}}.{{sfn|Augendre|2016|p=108}} It was won by the [[Belgium|Belgian]] cyclist [[Philippe Thys]].\n\nThe day the Tour began, [[Franz Ferdinand, Archduke of Austria]] was assassinated in [[Sarajevo]], marking the start of [[World War I]]. On 3 August [[Germany]] invaded [[Belgium]] and declared war on [[France]], making this Tour the last for five years, until [[1919 Tour de France|1919]]. The three men who won the Tour between 1907 and 1910 would die in the war.<ref>Wheatcroft, Geoffrey. ''Le Tour: a history of the Tour de France, 1903-2003'', p. 59. London: Pocket Books, 2003.</ref>\n\n==Innovations and changes==\nNot much changed from the [[1913 Tour de France]], the most important novelty was the introduction of frame numbers.<ref name=officialResults>{{cite web|url=http://www.letour.fr/HISTO/us/TDF/1914/histoire.html |title=1914 - 12th Tour de France |publisher=[[Amaury Sport Organisation|ASO]] |accessdate=30 May 2009 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/5hDNEHjO9?url=http://www.letour.fr/HISTO/TDF/1914/fr/annee.html |archivedate=1 June 2009 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\nPhilippe Thys, who had won the 1913 Tour de France, was returning in 1914 and considered favourite, together with his teammate [[Henri P\u00e9lissier]].{{sfn|McGann|McGann|2006|pp=47\u201350}} Apart from him six other previous Tour de France winners started the race: [[Louis Trousselier]], [[Lucien Petit-Breton]], [[Octave Lapize]], [[Fran\u00e7ois Faber]], [[Odile Defraye]] and [[Gustave Garrigou]]. Four more cyclists started the race that would later win a Tour de France: [[Firmin Lambot]], [[L\u00e9on Scieur]], [[Henri P\u00e9lissier]] and [[Lucien Buysse]]. This number of 11 former or future Tour de France winners on the start line is a record.<ref name=\"veloarchive\"/> In addition, Italian champion [[Costante Girardengo]], started the race,<ref name=\"tdf.nl\">{{cite web|url=http://www.wielercentrum.com/tourdefrance/achtergronden\\tourverhalen\\1914--Philippe-Thys-heerst-vanaf-de-eerste-dag-500.html|title=1914: Philippe Thys heerst vanaf de eerste dag|publisher=Tourdefrance.nl|date=19 March 2003|accessdate=31 May 2009|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120323021137/http://www.wielercentrum.com/tourdefrance/achtergronden//tourverhalen//1914--Philippe-Thys-heerst-vanaf-de-eerste-dag-500.html|archive-date=23 March 2012|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref> but Girardengo was not yet the champion from 1919 on, and was not the team leader.{{sfn|McGann|McGann|2006|pp=47\u201350}}\n\nIn 1914, the first cyclists from Australia started the Tour de France, [[Don Kirkham (cyclist)|Don Kirkham]] and [[Iddo Munro]]. They also finished the race, in 17th place and 20th place.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://sportal.com.au/tour-de-france-aussiesontour |title=Aussies and Kiwis on Tour |publisher=Sportal.com |accessdate=31 May 2009 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/5hEkCCF41?url=http://sportal.com.au/tour-de-france-aussiesontour |archivedate=2 June 2009 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\nThe cyclists used whistles, to warn other persons that they were coming (mainly downhill).<ref name=\"sky\"/>\n\n==Teams==\n{{main list|List of teams and cyclists in the 1914 Tour de France}}\n\n==Race overview==\n\n{{main|1914 Tour de France, Stage 1 to Stage 8|1914 Tour de France, Stage 9 to Stage 15}}\n\n[[File:Philippe Thys Paris-Roubaix 1919.jpg|thumb|upright|[[Philippe Thys]], the winner of the 1914 Tour de France]]\nThys was dominant in the entire race. Even though he only won the first stage, he finished in the top five every other stage.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.nieuwsdossier.nl/dossier/1914-07-26/Philippe+Thys+wint+Tour+de+France+1914 |title=Philippe Thys wint Tour de France 1914 |publisher=Nieuwsdossier |date=25 January 2008 |accessdate=31 May 2008 |language=Dutch |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/5hEkCbHG7?url=http://www.nieuwsdossier.nl/dossier/1914-07-26/Philippe+Thys+wint+Tour+de+France+1914 |archivedate=2 June 2009 |url-status=live  }}</ref>\nIn that first stage, [[Jean Rossius]] finished second with the same time. The second stage was won by Rossius, with Thys in the same time. Both had the same time, and the same finishing places, so they were both given the lead in the general classification.\n\nIn the third stage, the riders reached the first check point one hour late, after they had taken the wrong route and rode 30&nbsp;km in the wrong direction.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://aalst.courant.nu/index.php?page=3&mod=krantresultaat&q=ronde+van+frankrijk&datering=&krant=&qt=paragraaf&pagina=&sort=score+desc&paragraaf=69&doc=0&p=3&paragraaf=88&y=73|title=De derde rit - Cherbourg-Brest|date=3 July 1914|work=De Volksstem|publisher=aalst.courant.nu|language=Dutch|access-date=4 May 2010|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110724190346/http://aalst.courant.nu/index.php?page=3&mod=krantresultaat&q=ronde+van+frankrijk&datering=&krant=&qt=paragraaf&pagina=&sort=score+desc&paragraaf=69&doc=0&p=3&paragraaf=88&y=73|archive-date=24 July 2011|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref> The race was then stopped and restarted from the first check point.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://aalst.courant.nu/index.php?page=3&mod=krantresultaat&q=ronde+van+frankrijk&datering=&krant=&qt=paragraaf&pagina=&sort=score+desc&paragraaf=69&doc=0&p=3&paragraaf=88&y=73|title=De Ronde van Frankrijk - Nog de 3e rit: Cherborg-Brest|date=4 July 1914|work=De Volksstem|publisher=aalst.courant.nu|language=Dutch|access-date=4 May 2010|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110724190346/http://aalst.courant.nu/index.php?page=3&mod=krantresultaat&q=ronde+van+frankrijk&datering=&krant=&qt=paragraaf&pagina=&sort=score+desc&paragraaf=69&doc=0&p=3&paragraaf=88&y=73|archive-date=24 July 2011|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nThe lead remained shared between Rossius and Thys until after the fifth stage, when Thys got away from Rossius.{{sfn|McGann|McGann|2006|pp=47\u201350}} After that stage, P\u00e9lissier was third in the classification with only 5'27\" behind.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://memoire-du-cyclisme.net/eta_tdf_1903_1939/tdf1914_5.php |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120222105150/http://memoire-du-cyclisme.net/eta_tdf_1903_1939/tdf1914_5.php |archive-date=22 February 2012 |access-date=28 October 2016  |url-status=dead |title=12\u00e8me Tour de France 1914 - 5\u00e8me \u00e9tape |publisher=M\u00e9moire du cyclisme |language=French }}</ref>\n\nIn the sixth stage, the [[Pyrenees|Pyrenees mountains]] appeared. The stage was won by Lambot, with Thys only 7 minutes behind. The other competitors did worse, with P\u00e9lissier losing over 30 minutes and Rossius over one hour. Thys was firmly in the lead. In that stage, [[Ali Neffati]] was hit by a car from the organization, and could not continue. According to the rules, he did not have to finish the stage, and was given a time which allowed him to keep his 42nd place in the overall classification.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://memoire-du-cyclisme.net/eta_tdf_1903_1939/tdf1914_6.php |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120222105155/http://memoire-du-cyclisme.net/eta_tdf_1903_1939/tdf1914_6.php |archive-date=22 February 2012 |access-date=28 October 2016  |url-status=dead |title=12\u00e8me Tour de France 1914 - 6\u00e8me \u00e9tape |publisher=M\u00e9moire du cyclisme |language=French }}</ref> In the sixth stage, Girardengo crashed again, and retired from the Tour, never to come back.{{sfn|McGann|McGann|2006|pp=47\u201350}}\n\nThe weather was hot, and in the eighth stage, the cyclists did not want to race and cycled at a low speed. Tour organiser [[Henri Desgrange]] then stopped the race, and organised a sprint tournament, with semifinals and finals, which was won by Octave Lapize.<ref name=\"tdf.nl\"/> In the ninth stage, former winner Faber was penalised with 90 minutes, because he had been pushed and took drinks from a motor cyclist.<ref name=\"sky\">{{cite web|url=http://users.skynet.be/Tour1a/1903-2003%20centenaire.htm|language=Dutch|accessdate=31 May 2009|title=Ronde van Frankrijk 1903 - 2006}}</ref>\n\nP\u00e9lissier, still in second place, had done his best to win back time, but he only managed to win back a few minutes. After the thirteenth stage, he was still 31 minutes and 50 seconds behind.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cyclingrevealed.com/timeline/Race%20Snippets/TdF/TdF1914.htm|title=12th Tour de France 1914|author=Barry Boyce|accessdate=31 May 2009|publisher=Cycling Revealed}}</ref>\nIn the 14th stage to Dunkerque, Thys' bicycle broke. It was not allowed to get help while fixing your bicycle, and in the [[1913 Tour de France]], [[Eugene Christophe]] lost his chances of a victory by repairing his own bicycle. Thys decided to take the risk of a time penalty, and bought a new wheel at a shop.{{sfn|McGann|McGann|2006|pp=47\u201350}} This cost him a 30-minute penalty, which left Thys with only 1:50 ahead of P\u00e9lissier. P\u00e9lissier did his best to overcome the gap, but Thys followed him. In the stage to Dunkerque, P\u00e9lissier claimed spectators prevented him from getting away from Thys.<ref name=\"veloarchive\">{{cite web|url=http://www.veloarchive.com/races/tour/1914.php|title=1914: Thys in spite of P\u00e9lissier|accessdate=31 May 2009|date=14 August 2003|author=Tom James}}</ref> In the end, Thys stayed less than two minutes ahead of Henri P\u00e9lissier, and managed to keep that margin until the finish in Paris.<ref name=\"mdc1914\"/>\n\n==Results==\nIn each stage, all cyclists started together. The cyclist who reached the finish first, was the winner of the stage.\nThe time that each cyclist required to finish the stage was recorded. For the [[general classification in the Tour de France|general classification]], these times were added up; the cyclist with the least accumulated time was the race leader.\n\n===Stage results===\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|+ Stage characteristics and winners<ref name=\"mdc1914\">{{cite web|url=http://memoire-du-cyclisme.net/eta_tdf_1903_1939/tdf1914.php |publisher=M\u00e9moire du cyclisme |title=12\u00e8me Tour de France 1914 |language=French |accessdate=30 May 2009 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/5hDNEevaW?url=http://memoire-du-cyclisme.net/eta_tdf_1903_1939/tdf1914.php |archivedate=1 June 2009  |url-status=dead }}</ref>{{sfn|Augendre|2016|p=16}}<ref name=\"topten\">{{cite web|url=http://www.cvccbike.com/tour/top_ten.html#1914 |title=Tour de France GC top ten |author=Arian Zwegers |publisher=CVCC |accessdate=30 May 2009 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/5hDNF51go?url=http://www.cvccbike.com/tour/top_ten.html |archivedate=1 June 2009 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" | Stage\n! scope=\"col\" | Date\n! scope=\"col\" | Course\n! scope=\"col\" | Distance\n! scope=\"col\" colspan=\"2\" | Type{{efn|In 1914, there was no distinction in the rules between plain stages and mountain stages; the icons shown here indicate which stages included mountains.<ref name=\"mdc1914\"/>}}\n! scope=\"col\" | Winner\n! scope=\"col\" | Race leader\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | [[1914 Tour de France, Stage 1 to Stage 8#Stage 1|1]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" | 28 June || [[Paris]] to [[Le Havre]]\n| {{convert|388|km|mi|abbr=on}} || [[File:Plainstage.svg|20px|alt=|link=]] || Plain stage|| {{flagathlete|[[Philippe Thys]]|BEL}} || {{flagathlete|[[Philippe Thys]]|BEL}}{{efn|name=joint|From the first to the fifth stage, Thys and Rossius finished in the same times, leading the classification. In all sources, Thys is recorded as leader after the first stage, which he won, but from the second to the fifth stage, they are marked as joint leaders.<ref name=\"mdc1914\"/><ref name=\"topten\"/>}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | [[1914 Tour de France, Stage 1 to Stage 8#Stage 2|2]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" | 30 June || [[Le Havre]] to [[Cherbourg]]\n| {{convert|364|km|mi|abbr=on}} || [[File:Plainstage.svg|20px|alt=|link=]] || Plain stage|| {{flagathlete|[[Jean Rossius]]|BEL}} || {{flagathlete|[[Philippe Thys]]|BEL}}{{efn|name=joint}}<br/>{{flagathlete|[[Jean Rossius]]|BEL}}{{efn|name=joint}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | [[1914 Tour de France, Stage 1 to Stage 8#Stage 3|3]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" | 2 July || [[Cherbourg]] to [[Brest, France|Brest]]\n| {{convert|405|km|mi|abbr=on}} || [[File:Plainstage.svg|20px|alt=|link=]] || Plain stage|| {{flagathlete|[[Emile Engel]]|FRA}} || {{flagathlete|[[Philippe Thys]]|BEL}}{{efn|name=joint}}<br/>{{flagathlete|[[Jean Rossius]]|BEL}}{{efn|name=joint}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | [[1914 Tour de France, Stage 1 to Stage 8#Stage 4|4]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;